{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-puzzle-js","path":"/puzzles/strategy/221","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h2>Question</h2>\n<p>Two immensely intelligent players, A &#x26; B, engage in a game, the rules of which are as follows. For a natural number <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span>, the board consists of numbers from <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span>. Each player takes turns to strike off a (new) number from the board. But, to make sure <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span> doesn't affect who wins, there is an added rule. Once you strike off a number, you also have to strike off all its divisors in that same chance, irrespective of whether any of those divisors were already marked. The player to strike off the last number on the board wins.</p>\n<p>Can A construct a winning strategy?</p>\n<p>Note: The question asks for the existence of the strategy, not to devise the strategy itself.</p>\n<h2>Hint</h2>\n<p>Can one player copy the strategy of the other?</p>\n<h2>Answer</h2>\n<p>For a given <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span>, either <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> has a winning strategy or <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span>. If <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span> has the strategy, then <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> can strike 1 and copy <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span>'s strategy.</p>\n<h2>Solution</h2>\n<p>There is no simple winning strategy, based on the initial number <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span>, that A can use to win the game. We'll use the common strategy stealing argument.</p>\n<h3>Determinism</h3>\n<p>The game can be represented as a tree, where each node represents a possible state of the game, and the children represent valid moves to the next states.</p>\n<p>For instance, for <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N=5</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">5</span></span></span></span></span>, the root node is (5, 4, 3, 2, 1). There will be <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N=5</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">5</span></span></span></span></span> children nodes directly from the root node, and so on.</p>\n<p>Let \"level\" be the number of turns completed so far.</p>\n<p>At level <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span></span>, we have the root node. All the states that can be reached by striking one number (and its divisors) are at level 1. And so on.</p>\n<p>The height of the tree is at most <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span> (finite).</p>\n<p>Many nodes might hold the same state. All the leaf nodes look like empty sets where all numbers are struck off. (<del>5, 4, 3, 2, 1</del>). If this node is at an odd level then player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> has won. Otherwise, the player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span> has won.</p>\n<p>Let's color our game tree to represent the winning player in each possible end state. We color a leaf node \"red\" if the end state it represents is a win for Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span>, and blue if it's a win for Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span>. All leaf nodes at odd levels are red. And those at even levels are blue.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 200px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 64%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"tree\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/bfdfb6197e9eca9e5c91113b296d2ad1/56d15/221_tree.drawio.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/bfdfb6197e9eca9e5c91113b296d2ad1/77dd4/221_tree.drawio.png 50w,\n/static/bfdfb6197e9eca9e5c91113b296d2ad1/effb6/221_tree.drawio.png 100w,\n/static/bfdfb6197e9eca9e5c91113b296d2ad1/56d15/221_tree.drawio.png 200w,\n/static/bfdfb6197e9eca9e5c91113b296d2ad1/a8a0d/221_tree.drawio.png 300w,\n/static/bfdfb6197e9eca9e5c91113b296d2ad1/d9f49/221_tree.drawio.png 400w,\n/static/bfdfb6197e9eca9e5c91113b296d2ad1/b7e05/221_tree.drawio.png 651w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"eager\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Note that both players will try to move rationally toward their favored colored children nodes. Hence we can propagate these colors up.\nWe consider the following cases:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>If all children of a node are red, then that node itself becomes red, regardless of the level (odd or even). Same for blue.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>If a node has both red and blue children, it depends on the player. If it is at an <strong>even</strong> level, then it is Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span>'s turn. Otherwise, Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span> is in control. If a node at an even level has at least one red child node, then we can color this node as red, and delete the blue children nodes. This is because Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> will rationally move towards the winning state only. Similarly, we can propagate the blue nodes.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<!-- \nOnce a node is colored red, it is guaranteed that all the children nodes stay red. If there were any blue children, then those must have been discarded. Similarly, if a node is blue, all its children must be blue.\n-->\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 200px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 64%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"tree\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/e38dfcee819402d86ad27c9c90598217/56d15/221_tree2.drawio.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/e38dfcee819402d86ad27c9c90598217/77dd4/221_tree2.drawio.png 50w,\n/static/e38dfcee819402d86ad27c9c90598217/effb6/221_tree2.drawio.png 100w,\n/static/e38dfcee819402d86ad27c9c90598217/56d15/221_tree2.drawio.png 200w,\n/static/e38dfcee819402d86ad27c9c90598217/a8a0d/221_tree2.drawio.png 300w,\n/static/e38dfcee819402d86ad27c9c90598217/d9f49/221_tree2.drawio.png 400w,\n/static/e38dfcee819402d86ad27c9c90598217/b7e05/221_tree2.drawio.png 651w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"eager\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Thus, we can completely color the entire tree including the root node. It will either be entirely red or entirely blue.\nThis means that if both the players are rational geniuses, the winner is predetermined from the value of <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<h3>Existence of a Winning Strategy</h3>\n<p>Now, we examine the color of the root node. If it's red, Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> has a winning strategy right from the start. But can it be blue?</p>\n<p>Let's investigate this in detail.\nFrom the root node, there can be <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span> children, associated with striking each corresponding number. Consider all children associated with strike the number <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6595em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span></span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>></mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i>1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6986em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span></span>. If any one of these children is red, then the root node must be red. But if all are blue, that means that Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span> can force a win from any of these states. In other words, regardless of what player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> strikes (<span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span>), player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span> can push the game into a guaranteed win for player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<!-- \nNote that only the player $A$ can start with striking $1$ - a state only accessible from the root node. \n-->\n<p>But wait! There's a special move Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> can make: striking out 1. Thus, Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span> is put into the same position Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> was in at the start. From here, player B can choose to strike a number from <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span>, and player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> can force a win from here on, by copying the strategy of player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>The special state (<del>1</del>, 2,..., N) is only accessible from the root node. Because of an extra node, all the level numbers switch from odd to even and vice versa. Incidentally, this subtree will look exactly like the root tree with reverse colors (and also with one subtree cut-off, corresponding to this node). Thus, the root of the subtree representing this new game state is <strong>red</strong> because all the nodes from this point forward are red.</p>\n<p>In conclusion, Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span></span> always has a winning strategy in the Game of Divisors. By either making a move that leads directly to a winning game state or by striking out 1 and then mirroring Player <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span>'s ideal moves to force a win.</p>\n<p>This is a non-constructive strategy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Script</h3>\n<!-- \nThis game has nothing to do with dynamic programming or number theory. It is an example of how simple rules can sometimes lead to complex problems. \n-->\n<p>Using a script to generate the first move for a few values of <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>Find the <a href=\"https://colab.research.google.com/gist/varun-seth/86be5b460f6df480923a685bd4905635/puzzle_221_game_of_divisors.ipynb#sandboxMode=true\">Colab Script here</a>.</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th align=\"center\"><span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span></span></th>\n<th align=\"center\">     First move</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">1</td>\n<td align=\"center\">1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">2</td>\n<td align=\"center\">2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">3</td>\n<td align=\"center\">1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">4</td>\n<td align=\"center\">2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">5</td>\n<td align=\"center\">4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">6</td>\n<td align=\"center\">6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">7</td>\n<td align=\"center\">1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">8</td>\n<td align=\"center\">7</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">9</td>\n<td align=\"center\">7</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td align=\"center\">10</td>\n<td align=\"center\">6</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<!--\n|  11   |                 10                  |\n|  12   |                  5                  |\n|  13   |                  6                  |\n|  14   |                 14                  |\n|  15   |                 12                  |\n|  16   |                 14                  |\n|  17   |                 10                  |\n|  18   |                  5                  |\n|  19   |                 14                  |\n|  20   |                  9                  |\n|  21   |                 21                  |\n|  22   |                 22                  |\n|  23   |                 18                  |\n|  24   |                 20                  |\n|  25   |                  8                  |\n|  26   |                 23                  |\n|  27   |                 27                  |\n|  28   |                  1                  |\n|  29   |                 29                  |\n|  30   |                 15                  |\n-->\n<p>Indeed, the first player always wins, but has to often start by striking  <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>","frontmatter":{"puzzleId":221,"difficulty":"deadly","category":"strategy","title":"Game of Divisors"}}},"pageContext":{"puzzleId":221,"previousPuzzleRoute":"/puzzles/strategy/220","nextPuzzleRoute":"/puzzles/strategy/222","category":"strategy"}},"staticQueryHashes":["3649515864","764694655"],"slicesMap":{}}